Task 2: Build Containerized Test Environments for Two Applications
Problem Statement
Design and implement two independent, containerized test environments â one for a Python web application and one for a Node.js web application â such that running a single docker build followed by docker run --rm for each image executes all unit tests and exits with code 0 on success or non-zero on any test failure.

You decide the application logic, test cases, Dockerfile strategy, dependency management, and directory layout. The only constraints are listed in the acceptance criteria below.

Constraints:

Each application must expose at least three HTTP routes, one of which performs a calculation with URL parameters.
Each test suite must contain at least five distinct test cases covering normal inputs, edge cases, and an invalid-route check.
No test may depend on a running container or external network call; all tests must run entirely inside the image at build-run time.
Images must be built from official base images pulled from Docker Hub (python:3.9-slim and node:18-alpine are recommended starting points, but you may choose equivalents).
Acceptance Criteria:

docker run --rm <your-python-image> and docker run --rm <your-nodejs-image> each complete with exit code 0, and the terminal output shows a per-test pass/fail summary with a total count of at least five tests passing for each image.

Introducing a deliberate bug into one application route (for example, returning the wrong HTTP status code) causes the corresponding docker run --rm command to exit with a non-zero code and print which test failed, without affecting the other image.

Task 3: Implement a Multi-Service CI Pipeline That Gates Deployment
Problem Statement
Design and implement a CI pipeline â using Docker Compose as the orchestration layer and a shell script as the pipeline runner â that builds both images, runs both test suites in parallel, and only starts the application services if all tests pass. The pipeline must produce a structured exit code (0 for full success, non-zero for any failure) and write a plain-text summary report to a file on the host.

You decide the Compose service topology, the pipeline script logic, the health-check strategy, and the report format. The constraints and acceptance criteria below define what the finished system must demonstrate.

Constraints:

The pipeline script must not hard-code image names or service names; it must read them from environment variables or a configuration file that you define.
Application services must not start if either test service exits non-zero; enforce this in the pipeline script, not solely through Compose depends_on.
The summary report file must record: timestamp, pass/fail status for each test service, and the HTTP health-check result for each application service.
The pipeline must clean up all containers and anonymous volumes after it finishes, whether it succeeded or failed (use a trap or equivalent).
Acceptance Criteria:

Running the pipeline script from a clean state (no pre-built images, no running containers) completes end-to-end: both images build, both test suites pass, both application services start, both /health endpoints return HTTP 200 verified by curl --fail, and the summary report file exists on the host with all four required fields populated.

When one test suite is made to fail (by injecting a bug as in Task 2), the pipeline script exits non-zero, the application services are never started (confirmed by docker ps showing no running containers for those services), and the summary report records the failure â all without manual intervention after the initial script invocation.

Expected Outcomes
Two Docker images that encapsulate complete, self-contained test environments and enforce a pass/fail exit code boundary usable by any CI system.
A single pipeline script that a CI orchestrator (Jenkins, GitLab CI, or GitHub Actions) could invoke as a build step with no modification other than setting the environment variables you defined.
Conclusion
This lab demonstrates that containerized test environments eliminate "works on my machine" failures by making the runtime fully reproducible from a Dockerfile. Gating deployment on a structured exit code â rather than on a human reading terminal output â is the foundational pattern that makes CI pipelines reliable at scale. The same Docker Compose and shell-script approach you built here maps directly onto the agent-based job model used by Jenkins, GitLab CI, and GitHub Actions.
